{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8003dff7-25b5-465d-8c3f-98687daade5b","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After a SDK update, this is what brings your MAUI workload back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads that are already recorded but may have corrupted or missing files. It doesn't fetch newer versions, so it won't fix a version mismatch caused by a SDK update.\n\n**TL;DR:** `repair` fixes broken installs; `update` pulls versions compatible with your new SDK. You want `update`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-*`) appears, and check the build error for any missing workload IDs you may need to install explicitly with `dotnet workload install <id>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"78fa8fe4-97f8-48c2-91cf-7a2a9af54ffd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":289,"requestId":"9814:23E21D:15F9284:1883FA9:6A051DE7"},"id":"ee319c43-0534-4b3f-bf6e-c2cb223284fc","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:57:20.169Z","parentId":"b3fe83be-a73f-40ec-828c-0b594472d404"}
